...who wants to see you.
He says you have his daughter here.

715
00:52:16,926 --> 00:52:18,171
I say!

716
00:52:19,387 --> 00:52:21,344
Well, send the blackguard up.

717
00:52:21,472 --> 00:52:23,429
He may not be a blackguard, Higgins.

718
00:52:23,515 --> 00:52:26,185
Nonsense. Of course
he's a blackguard, Pickering.

719
00:52:26,269 --> 00:52:28,640
I'm afraid we'll have some trouble
with him.

720
00:52:28,729 --> 00:52:33,225
No, I think not. Any trouble to be had,
he'll have it with me. Not I with him.

721
00:52:36,487 --> 00:52:37,897
Doolittle, sir.

722
00:52:44,327 --> 00:52:46,406
-Professor Higgins?
-Here!

723
00:52:47,583 --> 00:52:48,614
Where?

724
00:52:49,167 --> 00:52:51,041
Good morning, Governor.

725
00:52:51,461 --> 00:52:54,497
I come about a very serious matter,
Governor.

726
00:52:58,009 --> 00:53:00,049
Brought up in Houndslow.

727
00:53:00,720 --> 00:53:02,677
Mother Welsh, I should think.

728
00:53:03,681 --> 00:53:05,258
What is it you want, Doolittle?

729
00:53:05,350 --> 00:53:07,888
I want my daughter, that's what I want.
See?

730
00:53:07,977 --> 00:53:10,468
Of course you do.
You're her father, aren't you?

731
00:53:10,563 --> 00:53:13,184
I'm glad to see you have a spark
of family feeling left.

732
00:53:13,274 --> 00:53:15,896
She's in there. Yes, take her away at once.

733
00:53:16,069 --> 00:53:17,100
What?

734
00:53:17,653 --> 00:53:21,603
Take her away. Do you think I am going
to keep your daughter for you?

735
00:53:21,740 --> 00:53:24,492
Now, is this reasonable, Governor?

736
00:53:24,659 --> 00:53:27,696
Is it fairity to take advantage
of a man like that?

737
00:53:27,871 --> 00:53:31,121
The girl belongs to me. You got 'er.
Where do I come in?

738
00:53:31,583 --> 00:53:35,251
How dare you come here
and attempt to blackmail me!

739
00:53:35,840 --> 00:53:37,797
You sent her here on purpose!

740
00:53:37,925 --> 00:53:41,210
Don't take a man up like that, Governor.

741
00:53:41,386 --> 00:53:43,544
The police shall take you up.
This is a plan...

742
00:53:43,638 --> 00:53:46,011
...a plot to extort money by threats.

743
00:53:46,100 --> 00:53:48,056
I shall telephone the police.

744
00:53:48,185 --> 00:53:51,185
Have I asked you for a brass farthin'?

745
00:53:51,688 --> 00:53:55,271
I leave it to this gentleman 'ere.
Have I said a word about money?

746
00:53:55,359 --> 00:53:57,517
Well, what else did you come for?

747
00:53:59,404 --> 00:54:01,396
What would a bloke come for?

748
00:54:01,781 --> 00:54:03,690
Be 'uman, Governor.

749
00:54:08,788 --> 00:54:11,741
Alfred, you sent her here on purpose.

750
00:54:11,874 --> 00:54:13,534
So help me, Governor, I never did.

751
00:54:13,625 --> 00:54:15,036
How did you know she was here?

752
00:54:15,127 --> 00:54:17,998
I'd tell you, Governor,
if you'd let me get a word in.

753
00:54:18,089 --> 00:54:20,959
I'm willing to tell ya.
I'm wanting to tell ya.

754
00:54:21,216 --> 00:54:23,007
I'm waiting to tell ya!

755
00:54:24,719 --> 00:54:28,766
You know, Pickering, this chap's got
a certain natural gift of rhetoric.

756
00:54:28,976 --> 00:54:31,893
Observe the rhythm
of his native woodnotes wild.

757
00:54:32,145 --> 00:54:36,096
'"l'm willing to tell you. I'm wanting
to tell you. I'm waiting to tell you.'"

758
00:54:36,192 --> 00:54:38,350
That's the Welsh strain in 'im.

759
00:54:38,610 --> 00:54:41,231
How did you know Eliza was here
if you didn't send 'er?

760
00:54:41,321 --> 00:54:44,820
Well, she sent back for her luggage
and I got to 'ear about it.

761
00:54:44,907 --> 00:54:47,613
She said she didn't want no clothes.

762
00:54:48,245 --> 00:54:52,906
What was I to think from that, Governor?
I ask you, as a parent, what was I to think?

763
00:54:53,374 --> 00:54:57,123
So you came here to rescue her
from worse than death, eh?

764
00:54:57,462 --> 00:54:59,953
-Yes, sir, Governor. That's right.
-Yes.

765
00:55:00,339 --> 00:55:01,750
Mrs. Pearce!

766
00:55:03,175 --> 00:55:06,627
Eliza's father has come to take her away.
Give her to him, will you?

767
00:55:06,721 --> 00:55:10,136
Now wait a minute, Governor.
Wait a minute.

768
00:55:11,100 --> 00:55:13,769
You and me is men o' the world, ain't we?

769
00:55:14,269 --> 00:55:18,352
Men of the world, are we?
Perhaps you'd better go, Mrs. Pearce.

770
00:55:18,442 --> 00:55:20,150
I think so indeed, sir!

771
00:55:20,569 --> 00:55:21,850
Here, Governor.

772
00:55:22,279 --> 00:55:25,197
I've took a sort of a fancy to you and...

773
00:55:28,535 --> 00:55:31,904
...if you want the girl, I ain't so set
on 'avin' her home again...

774
00:55:31,997 --> 00:55:34,914
...but what I might be open to
is an arrangement.

775
00:55:35,334 --> 00:55:37,741
All I ask is my rights as a father.

776
00:55:37,836 --> 00:55:41,501
You're the last man alive to expect me
to let her go for nothing.

777
00:55:41,840 --> 00:55:45,090
I can see you're a straight sort, Governor.

778
00:55:45,177 --> 00:55:46,208
So...

779
00:55:46,470 --> 00:55:50,253
...what's a five pound note to you?
An' what's Eliza to me?

780
00:55:50,890 --> 00:55:52,598
I think you should know, Doolittle...

781
00:55:52,683 --> 00:55:55,851
...that Mr. Higgins' intentions
are entirely honorable.

782
00:55:56,229 --> 00:56:00,061
Of course they are, Governor.
If I thought they wasn't, I'd ask 50.

783
00:56:00,566 --> 00:56:03,401
You mean, you'd sell your daughter
for 50 pounds?

784
00:56:03,485 --> 00:56:05,232
Have you no morals, man?

785
00:56:08,242 --> 00:56:12,322
No, I can't afford 'em, Governor. Neither
could you if you was as poor as me.

786
00:56:12,413 --> 00:56:14,619
Not that I mean any 'arm, but...

787
00:56:14,706 --> 00:56:18,207
...if Eliza is gonna have a bit out o' this,
why not me, too?

788
00:56:19,504 --> 00:56:20,583
Why not?

789
00:56:23,508 --> 00:56:25,999
Look at it my way. What am l?

790
00:56:27,012 --> 00:56:31,091
I ask ya, what am l? I'm one
o' the undeserving poor, that's what I am.

791
00:56:31,182 --> 00:56:33,221
Think what that means to a man.

792
00:56:33,309 --> 00:56:37,010
It means he's up against
middle-class morality for all the time.

793
00:56:37,605 --> 00:56:41,554
If there's anything goin' an' I ask
for a bit of it, it's always the same story:

794
00:56:41,650 --> 00:56:44,271
'"You're undeservin', so you can't have it.'"

795
00:56:44,444 --> 00:56:48,443
But my needs is as great as the most
deservin' widows that ever got money...

796
00:56:48,532 --> 00:56:53,028
...out of six different charities in one week
for the death o' the same 'usband.

797
00:56:53,120 --> 00:56:56,622
I don't need less than a deservin' man,
I need more.

798
00:56:57,084 --> 00:57:00,085
I don't eat less 'earty than he does
and I drink...

799
00:57:00,879 --> 00:57:02,124
...a lot more.

800
00:57:02,422 --> 00:57:04,415
I'm playin' straight with you.

801
00:57:04,508 --> 00:57:08,209
I ain't pretendin' to be deservin'.
No, I'm undeservin'...

802
00:57:08,720 --> 00:57:12,765
...and I mean to go on bein' undeservin'.
I like it an' that's the truth.

803
00:57:12,849 --> 00:57:16,432
But will you take advantage
of a man's nature...

804
00:57:16,687 --> 00:57:20,138
...do him out of the price of
his own daughter, what he's brought up...

805
00:57:20,231 --> 00:57:22,936
...fed and clothed
by the sweat of his brow...

806
00:57:23,651 --> 00:57:28,313
...till she's growed big enough
to be interestin' to you two gentlemen?

807
00:57:30,241 --> 00:57:33,574
Is five pounds unreasonable,
I put it to you?

808
00:57:33,953 --> 00:57:35,578
And I leave it to you.

809
00:57:38,416 --> 00:57:41,998
You know, Pickering, if we took this man
in hand for three months...

810
00:57:42,086 --> 00:57:46,501
...he could choose between a seat in
the Cabinet and a popular pulpit in Wales.

811
00:57:46,926 --> 00:57:50,674
-We'd better give 'im a fiver.
-He'll make bad use of it, I'm afraid.

812
00:57:50,763 --> 00:57:52,802
Not me, Governor, so 'elp me I won't.

813
00:57:52,890 --> 00:57:55,381
Just one good spree
for meself an' the missus...

814
00:57:55,476 --> 00:57:58,560
...givin' pleasure to ourselves
and employment to others.

815
00:57:58,646 --> 00:58:01,516
An' satisfaction to you to know
it ain't been throwed away.

816
00:58:01,607 --> 00:58:03,266
You couldn't spend it better.

817
00:58:03,358 --> 00:58:06,110
This is irresistible. Let's give 'im ten.

818
00:58:06,487 --> 00:58:08,693
The missus wouldn't have the 'eart
to spend ten.

819
00:58:08,780 --> 00:58:10,488
Ten pounds is a lot o' money.

820
00:58:10,574 --> 00:58:14,108
Makes a man feel prudent-like,
and then goodbye to 'appiness.

821
00:58:14,535 --> 00:58:18,581
No, you just give me what I ask, Governor.
Not a penny less, not a penny more.

822
00:58:18,665 --> 00:58:21,998
I rather draw the line at encouraging
this sort of immorality.

823
00:58:22,085 --> 00:58:24,160
Why don't you marry that missus of yours?

824
00:58:24,253 --> 00:58:27,670
After all, marriage isn't so frightening.
You married Eliza's mother.

825
00:58:27,757 --> 00:58:29,381
Who told you that, Governor?

826
00:58:29,467 --> 00:58:32,302
Well, nobody told me.
I concluded, naturally....

827
00:58:36,226 --> 00:58:39,760
If we listen to this man for another minute
we'll have no convictions left.

828
00:58:39,854 --> 00:58:42,689
-Five pounds, I think you said.
-Thank you, Governor.

829
00:58:42,773 --> 00:58:44,148
Are you sure you won't have ten?

830
00:58:44,233 --> 00:58:46,522
No. No, perhaps another time.

831
00:58:48,487 --> 00:58:49,732
I beg your pardon, miss.

832
00:58:49,822 --> 00:58:52,573
I won't say those ruddy vowels
one more time.

833
00:58:52,658 --> 00:58:54,317
Blimey, it's Eliza.

834
00:58:54,618 --> 00:58:57,192
I never thought she'd clean up
so good-looking.

835
00:58:57,288 --> 00:58:59,280
She does me credit, don't she?

836
00:58:59,373 --> 00:59:01,910
What are you doin' here?

837
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:06,461
Now, you hold your tongue and don't
you give these gentlemen none o' your lip.

838
00:59:07,005 --> 00:59:10,338
If you have any trouble with 'er,
give 'er a few licks o' the strap.

839
00:59:10,425 --> 00:59:12,713
That's the way to improve 'er mind.

840
00:59:13,011 --> 00:59:15,716
Well, good morning, gentlemen.
Cheerio, Eliza.

841
00:59:19,392 --> 00:59:23,092
There's a man for you.
A philosophical genius of the first water.

842
00:59:24,691 --> 00:59:26,933
Write to Mr. Ezra Wallingford
and tell him...

843
00:59:27,027 --> 00:59:30,360
...if he wants a lecturer, to get in touch
with Mr. Doolittle...

844
00:59:30,446 --> 00:59:34,230
...a common dustman, one of
the most original moralists in England.

845
00:59:34,533 --> 00:59:36,325
What did he come for?

846
00:59:36,578 --> 00:59:37,609
Say your vowels.

847
00:59:37,704 --> 00:59:39,743
I know me vowels.
I knew 'em before I come.

848
00:59:39,830 --> 00:59:41,111
If you know them, say them.

849
00:59:41,207 --> 00:59:44,291
Ahyee, e, iyee, ow, you.

850
00:59:45,295 --> 00:59:47,536
A, E, l, O, U.

851
00:59:48,005 --> 00:59:50,922
That's what I said. Ahyee, e, iyee, ow, you.

852
00:59:51,008 --> 00:59:53,843
That's what I've said for three days
an' I won't no more.

853
00:59:53,927 --> 00:59:57,047
I know it's difficult, Miss Doolittle,
but try to understand.

854
00:59:57,139 --> 01:00:00,342
There's no use explaining.
As a military man you should know that.

855
01:00:00,434 --> 01:00:01,976
Drilling is what she needs.

856
01:00:02,060 --> 01:00:04,467
Leave her alone or she'll turn to you
for sympathy.

857
01:00:04,562 --> 01:00:07,599
Very well, if you insist,
but have a little patience with her.

858
01:00:07,691 --> 01:00:08,889
Of course.

859
01:00:09,526 --> 01:00:10,901
Say '"A.'"

860
01:00:11,069 --> 01:00:13,227
You ain't got no 'eart, you ain't.

861
01:00:20,747 --> 01:00:24,792
I promise you, you'll say your vowels
correctly before this day is out...

862
01:00:25,085 --> 01:00:29,414
...or there'll be no lunch,
no dinner, and no chocolates.

863
01:00:40,891 --> 01:00:44,390
'"Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait

864
01:00:45,354 --> 01:00:48,640
'"You'll be sorry
But your tears will be too late

865
01:00:49,858 --> 01:00:54,235
'"You'll be broke and I'll have money
Will I help you? Don't be funny!

866
01:00:54,404 --> 01:00:57,571
'"Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait

867
01:00:58,909 --> 01:01:02,028
'"Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Till you're sick

868
01:01:03,329 --> 01:01:06,617
'"And you screams
To fetch a doctor double-quick

869
01:01:07,836 --> 01:01:12,499
'"l'll be off a second later
And go straight to the theater

870
01:01:12,633 --> 01:01:15,588
'"Ho, ho, ho, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait!

871
01:01:21,433 --> 01:01:25,099
'"Just you wait
Until we're swimmin' in the sea

872
01:01:30,025 --> 01:01:33,524
'"And you get the cramp
a little ways from me

873
01:01:34,447 --> 01:01:38,610
'"When you yell you're gonna drown
I'll get dressed and go to town

874
01:01:43,746 --> 01:01:46,582
'"Just you wait!

875
01:01:50,295 --> 01:01:55,504
'"One day I'll be famous
I'll be proper and prim

876
01:01:55,886 --> 01:02:00,761
'"Go to St. James so often
I will call it St. Jim

877
01:02:01,766 --> 01:02:06,559
'"One evening the king will say
'Oh, Liza, old thing

878
01:02:07,313 --> 01:02:12,603
'"'l want all of England your praises to sing

879
01:02:13,610 --> 01:02:17,395
'"'Next week on the 20th of May

880
01:02:18,157 --> 01:02:22,154
'"'l proclaim Liza Doolittle Day

881
01:02:23,620 --> 01:02:28,413
'"'All the people will celebrate
the glory of you

882
01:02:28,667 --> 01:02:33,494
'"'And whatever you wish and want
I gladly will do'

883
01:02:34,507 --> 01:02:39,417
'"'Thanks a lot, King,' says I
in a manner well-bred

884
01:02:40,470 --> 01:02:44,601
'"'But all I want is 'Enry 'lggins' 'ead'

885
01:02:46,687 --> 01:02:47,469
'"'Done!'

886
01:02:47,562 --> 01:02:49,769
'"Says the king with a stroke

887
01:02:51,357 --> 01:02:54,359
'"'Guard, run and bring in the bloke'

888
01:02:55,779 --> 01:02:59,527
'"Then they'll march you, 'Enry 'lggins,
to the wall

889
01:03:00,700 --> 01:03:02,408
'"And the king will tell me:

890
01:03:02,493 --> 01:03:04,570
'"'Liza, sound the call'

891
01:03:05,497 --> 01:03:08,450
'"As they raise their rifles higher

892
01:03:08,583 --> 01:03:12,200
'"l'll shout: 'Ready, aim, fire!'

893
01:03:14,129 --> 01:03:17,878
'"Ho, ho, ho, 'Enry 'lggins, down you go

894
01:03:19,677 --> 01:03:22,463
'"Just you wait! '"

895
01:04:01,844 --> 01:04:04,086
All right, Eliza, say it again.

896
01:04:04,973 --> 01:04:07,594
'"The rine in Spine...

897
01:04:07,683 --> 01:04:10,719
'"...stais minely in the pline.'"

898
01:04:11,520 --> 01:04:15,305
'"The rain in Spain
stays mainly in the plain.'"

899
01:04:15,775 --> 01:04:16,889
Didn't I saiy that?

900
01:04:16,984 --> 01:04:20,518
No, Eliza, you didn't '"saiy'" that.
You didn't even '"say'" that.

901
01:04:20,904 --> 01:04:24,240
Every night before you go to bed,
where you used to say your prayers...

902
01:04:24,327 --> 01:04:25,525
...l want you to say:

903
01:04:25,620 --> 01:04:28,905
'"The rain in Spain
stays mainly in the plain.'"

904
01:04:29,081 --> 01:04:30,243
Fifty times.

905
01:04:30,791 --> 01:04:34,955
You'll get much further with the Lord
if you learn not to offend His ears.

906
01:04:35,713 --> 01:04:37,207
Now for your '"H's.'"

907
01:04:38,423 --> 01:04:40,380
Pickering, this is going to be ghastly.

908
01:04:40,467 --> 01:04:42,673
Control yourself, Higgins.
Give the girl a chance.

909
01:04:42,760 --> 01:04:45,715
I suppose you can't expect her
to get it right the first time.

910
01:04:45,806 --> 01:04:48,047
Come here, Eliza, and watch closely.

911
01:04:52,145 --> 01:04:53,852
Now, you see that flame?

912
01:04:54,147 --> 01:04:57,646
Every time you pronounce the letter '"H'"
correctly the flame will waver...

913
01:04:57,734 --> 01:05:01,019
...and every time you drop your '"H'"
the flame will remain stationary.

914
01:05:01,112 --> 01:05:02,819
That's how to know
you've done it correctly.

915
01:05:02,905 --> 01:05:04,779
In time, your ear will hear the difference.

916
01:05:04,866 --> 01:05:08,530
You'll see it better in the mirror.
Now listen carefully.

917
01:05:09,245 --> 01:05:12,162
'"ln Hartford, Hereford and Hampshire...

918
01:05:12,623 --> 01:05:15,626
'"...hurricanes hardly ever happen.'"

919
01:05:16,796 --> 01:05:19,084
Now you repeat that after me.

920
01:05:19,798 --> 01:05:23,333
'"ln Hartford, Hereford and Hampshire,
hurricanes hardly ever happen.'"

921
01:05:23,427 --> 01:05:28,303
'"ln 'artford, 'ereford and 'ampshire
'urricanes 'ardly hever 'appen.'"

922
01:05:28,432 --> 01:05:30,140
Oh, no, no!

923
01:05:30,267 --> 01:05:32,058
Have you no ear at all?

924
01:05:32,185 --> 01:05:34,344
-Should I do it over?
-No, please.

925
01:05:35,064 --> 01:05:37,685
Start from the very beginning.
Just do this.

926
01:05:46,950 --> 01:05:48,610
Go on, go on.

927
01:05:52,496 --> 01:05:54,739
Does the same thing hold true in lndia?

928
01:05:54,833 --> 01:05:57,917
Have they the peculiar habit
of not only dropping a letter...

929
01:05:58,002 --> 01:06:02,046
...but using it where it doesn't belong,
like '"hever'" instead of '"ever'"?

930
01:06:25,407 --> 01:06:26,521
The girl, Higgins!

931
01:06:26,616 --> 01:06:27,814
Go on. Go on.

932
01:06:29,786 --> 01:06:32,620
''Poor Professor Higgins

933
01:06:34,040 --> 01:06:36,911
''Poor Professor Higgins

934
01:06:38,252 --> 01:06:42,380
'"Night and day he slaves away

935
01:06:43,215 --> 01:06:46,715
'"Oh, poor Professor Higgins

936
01:06:48,262 --> 01:06:52,211
'"All day long on his feet

937
01:06:52,766 --> 01:06:56,718
'"Up and down until he's numb

938
01:06:57,231 --> 01:07:01,145
'"Doesn't rest, doesn't eat

939
01:07:01,652 --> 01:07:04,404
'"Doesn't touch a crumb'"

940
01:07:08,533 --> 01:07:09,731
Again, Eliza.

941
01:07:10,035 --> 01:07:12,905
How kind of you to let me come.

