How do you do?

1190
01:27:06,616 --> 01:27:09,534
-Mrs. Eynsford-Hill, Miss Doolittle.
-How do you do?

1191
01:27:09,619 --> 01:27:11,113
How do you do?

1192
01:27:11,371 --> 01:27:13,245
And Freddy Eynsford-Hill.

1193
01:27:14,416 --> 01:27:15,958
How do you do?

1194
01:27:18,294 --> 01:27:19,872
How do you do?

1195
01:27:20,630 --> 01:27:21,911
Miss Doolittle.

1196
01:27:22,174 --> 01:27:25,340
Good afternoon, Professor Higgins.

1197
01:27:34,560 --> 01:27:37,265
The first race was very exciting,
Miss Doolittle.

1198
01:27:37,354 --> 01:27:39,596
I'm so sorry that you missed it.

1199
01:27:39,815 --> 01:27:41,641
Will it rain, do you think?

1200
01:27:41,945 --> 01:27:46,024
'"The rain in Spain stays mainly
in the plain.'"

1201
01:27:51,161 --> 01:27:55,658
'"But in Hartford, Hereford and Hampshire,
hurricanes hardly ever happen.'"

1202
01:27:57,042 --> 01:27:58,501
How awfully funny.

1203
01:27:58,668 --> 01:28:02,120
What is wrong with that, young man?
I bet I got it right.

1204
01:28:02,423 --> 01:28:03,502
Smashing.

1205
01:28:03,799 --> 01:28:06,254
Has it suddenly turned chilly?

1206
01:28:06,760 --> 01:28:10,128
I do hope we won't have
any unseasonable cold spells.

1207
01:28:10,388 --> 01:28:12,381
They bring on so much influenza.

1208
01:28:12,474 --> 01:28:15,225
And the whole of our family
is susceptible to it.

1209
01:28:15,310 --> 01:28:19,639
My aunt died of influenza, so they said.

1210
01:28:20,189 --> 01:28:23,974
But it's my belief they done
the old woman in.

1211
01:28:25,194 --> 01:28:26,475
Done her in?

1212
01:28:27,113 --> 01:28:28,820
Yes, Lord love you.

1213
01:28:29,073 --> 01:28:31,314
Why should she die of influenza...

1214
01:28:31,575 --> 01:28:35,361
...when she'd come through diphtheria
right enough the year before.

1215
01:28:35,623 --> 01:28:37,829
Fairly blue with it she was.

1216
01:28:38,501 --> 01:28:40,374
They all thought she was dead.

1217
01:28:40,461 --> 01:28:44,589
But my father, he kept ladling gin
down her throat.

1218
01:28:49,553 --> 01:28:53,930
Then she come to so sudden
she bit the bowl off the spoon.

1219
01:28:55,225 --> 01:28:56,684
Dear me!

1220
01:28:57,853 --> 01:29:01,186
Now what call would a woman
with that strength in her...

1221
01:29:01,272 --> 01:29:03,182
...have to die of influenza?

1222
01:29:03,901 --> 01:29:08,194
And what become of her new straw hat
that should have come to me?

1223
01:29:10,781 --> 01:29:13,107
Somebody pinched it.

1224
01:29:14,369 --> 01:29:16,160
And what I say is:

1225
01:29:16,371 --> 01:29:19,324
Them 'as pinched it, done her in.

1226
01:29:20,583 --> 01:29:23,123
Done her in? '"Done her in,'" did you say?

1227
01:29:23,838 --> 01:29:25,498
Whatever does it mean?

1228
01:29:25,632 --> 01:29:30,210
That's the new small talk.
'"To do somebody in'" means to kill them.

1229
01:29:30,886 --> 01:29:33,971
But you surely don't believe
your aunt was killed?

1230
01:29:34,557 --> 01:29:35,837
Do I not?

1231
01:29:35,975 --> 01:29:40,969
Them she lived with would have killed her
for a hatpin, let alone a hat.

1232
01:29:41,396 --> 01:29:43,805
But it can't have been right
for your father...

1233
01:29:43,899 --> 01:29:46,734
...to pour spirits down her throat like that.

1234
01:29:47,111 --> 01:29:48,770
It might have killed her.

1235
01:29:48,862 --> 01:29:52,647
Not her. Gin was mother's milk to her.

1236
01:29:53,033 --> 01:29:58,158
Besides, he poured so much down
his own throat he knew the good of it.

1237
01:29:58,913 --> 01:30:00,657
Do you mean that he drank?

1238
01:30:00,748 --> 01:30:03,584
Drank? My word. Something chronic.

1239
01:30:07,422 --> 01:30:10,506
Here, what are you sniggering at?

1240
01:30:11,175 --> 01:30:14,297
The new small talk.
You do it so awfully well.

1241
01:30:14,514 --> 01:30:18,179
Well, if I was doing it proper,
what was you sniggering at?

1242
01:30:19,143 --> 01:30:21,433
Have I said anything I oughtn't?

1243
01:30:23,356 --> 01:30:24,934
Not at all, my dear.

1244
01:30:25,149 --> 01:30:27,106
Well, that's a mercy anyhow.

1245
01:30:30,112 --> 01:30:33,648
I don't know if there's time
before the next race to place a bet...

1246
01:30:33,742 --> 01:30:35,569
...but come, my dear.

1247
01:30:35,952 --> 01:30:39,617
I have a bet on number seven.
I should be so happy if you would take it.

1248
01:30:39,706 --> 01:30:41,829
You'll enjoy the race ever so much more.

1249
01:30:41,917 --> 01:30:43,541
That's very kind of you.

1250
01:30:43,627 --> 01:30:44,741
His name is Dover.

1251
01:30:44,836 --> 01:30:46,295
Come along.

1252
01:30:49,757 --> 01:30:51,667
'"There they are again

1253
01:30:51,760 --> 01:30:53,384
'"Lining up to run

1254
01:30:53,845 --> 01:30:55,553
'"Now they're holding steady

1255
01:30:55,638 --> 01:30:57,927
'"They are ready for it. Look!

1256
01:30:58,974 --> 01:31:01,216
'"lt has begun'"

1257
01:31:07,151 --> 01:31:08,942
Come on. Come on, Dover.

1258
01:31:09,903 --> 01:31:10,899
Come on.

1259
01:31:11,196 --> 01:31:12,822
Come on, Dover!

1260
01:31:12,949 --> 01:31:13,980
Come on!

1261
01:31:18,328 --> 01:31:22,492
Come on, Dover!
Move your bloomin' arse!

1262
01:31:29,005 --> 01:31:30,380
Oh, my dear.

1263
01:31:45,355 --> 01:31:49,222
You're not serious, Henry. You don't
expect to take her to the Embassy Ball.

1264
01:31:49,317 --> 01:31:50,859
Don't you think she's ready for it?

1265
01:31:50,943 --> 01:31:53,318
Dear Henry, she's ready for a canal barge.

1266
01:31:53,406 --> 01:31:55,648
Her language may need
a little refining, but--

1267
01:31:55,742 --> 01:31:59,359
Really, Henry, if you cannot see
how impossible this whole project is...

1268
01:31:59,453 --> 01:32:01,113
...then you must be potty about her.

1269
01:32:01,205 --> 01:32:03,282
I advise you to give up
and not put yourself...

1270
01:32:03,374 --> 01:32:04,952
...or this poor girl through any more.

1271
01:32:05,042 --> 01:32:07,580
It's the most fascinating venture
I've ever undertaken.

1272
01:32:07,670 --> 01:32:11,121
Pickering and I are at it from morning
till night. It fills our whole lives.

1273
01:32:11,214 --> 01:32:15,082
Teaching Eliza, talking to Eliza,
listening to Eliza, dressing Eliza.

1274
01:32:16,262 --> 01:32:19,796
You're a pretty pair of babies
playing with your live doll.

1275
01:32:19,890 --> 01:32:21,170
Here's the car.

1276
01:33:42,391 --> 01:33:43,422
Good evening, sir.

1277
01:33:43,517 --> 01:33:46,186
-Is dinner ready? I'm famished.
-Immediately, sir.

1278
01:33:46,269 --> 01:33:48,345
Good evening, Professor Higgins.

1279
01:34:05,955 --> 01:34:10,166
'"When she mentioned
how her aunt bit off the spoon

1280
01:34:10,917 --> 01:34:14,203
'"She completely done me in

1281
01:34:14,713 --> 01:34:18,082
'"And my heart went on
a journey to the moon

1282
01:34:18,675 --> 01:34:23,304
'"When she told about her father
and the gin

1283
01:34:23,974 --> 01:34:27,971
'"And I never saw a more enchanting farce

1284
01:34:28,687 --> 01:34:33,645
'"Than the moment when she shouted
'Move your bloomin'--''"

1285
01:34:34,359 --> 01:34:36,399
-Yes, sir?
-Is Miss Doolittle in?

1286
01:34:36,486 --> 01:34:38,313
Whom shall I say is calling?

1287
01:34:38,404 --> 01:34:41,691
Freddy Eynsford-Hill.
If she doesn't remember who I am...

1288
01:34:41,825 --> 01:34:44,742
...tell her I'm the chap
who was '"sniggering'" at her.

1289
01:34:44,828 --> 01:34:45,823
Yes, sir.

1290
01:34:45,912 --> 01:34:47,821
And will you give her these?

1291
01:34:48,289 --> 01:34:49,487
Wouldn't you like to come in?

1292
01:34:49,582 --> 01:34:51,705
They're having dinner,
but you may wait in the hall.

1293
01:34:51,793 --> 01:34:55,327
No, thank you. I want to drink in
the street where she lives.

1294
01:35:03,679 --> 01:35:08,637
'"l have often walked
down this street before

1295
01:35:09,476 --> 01:35:14,354
'"But the pavement always stayed
beneath my feet before

1296
01:35:15,109 --> 01:35:20,066
'"All at once am I several stories high

1297
01:35:20,739 --> 01:35:25,366
'"Knowing I'm on the street where you live

1298
01:35:26,661 --> 01:35:31,621
'"Are there lilac trees in the heart of town?

1299
01:35:32,335 --> 01:35:37,292
'"Can you hear a lark
in any other part of town?

1300
01:35:38,215 --> 01:35:43,043
'"Does enchantment pour
out of every door?

1301
01:35:43,846 --> 01:35:48,507
'"No, it's just on the street where you live

1302
01:35:50,060 --> 01:35:54,556
'"And, oh, the towering feeling

1303
01:35:55,399 --> 01:35:59,894
'"Just to know somehow you are near

1304
01:36:01,657 --> 01:36:06,153
'"The overpowering feeling

1305
01:36:06,703 --> 01:36:11,365
'"That any second you may suddenly appear

1306
01:36:12,918 --> 01:36:17,709
'"People stop and stare,
they don't bother me

1307
01:36:18,715 --> 01:36:23,377
'"For there's nowhere else on earth
that I would rather be

1308
01:36:24,679 --> 01:36:27,680
'"Let the time go by

1309
01:36:27,807 --> 01:36:31,805
'"l won't care if I

1310
01:36:32,562 --> 01:36:37,223
'"Can be here on the street where you live'"

1311
01:36:44,573 --> 01:36:46,482
I'm terribly sorry, sir.

1312
01:36:46,617 --> 01:36:49,736
Miss Doolittle says she doesn't want
to see anyone ever again.

1313
01:36:49,828 --> 01:36:51,538
But why? She was unbelievable.

1314
01:36:51,624 --> 01:36:54,790
So I've been told, sir.
Is there any further message?

1315
01:36:55,961 --> 01:36:57,206
Tell her that I'll wait.

1316
01:36:57,296 --> 01:36:59,703
But it might be days, sir, even weeks.

1317
01:36:59,798 --> 01:37:02,336
But don't you see? I'll be happier here.

1318
01:37:11,268 --> 01:37:15,929
'"People stop and stare,
they don't bother me

1319
01:37:17,273 --> 01:37:21,935
'"For there's nowhere else on earth
that I would rather be

1320
01:37:23,113 --> 01:37:25,983
'"Let the time go by

1321
01:37:26,657 --> 01:37:30,987
'"l won't care if I

1322
01:37:31,955 --> 01:37:36,616
'"Can be here on the street where you live'"

1323
01:37:46,804 --> 01:37:49,425
It really is, Higgins.
It's inhuman to continue.

1324
01:37:49,514 --> 01:37:52,551
Do you realize what you've got to teach
this girl in six weeks?

1325
01:37:52,643 --> 01:37:55,597
You've got to teach her to walk, talk,
address a duke, a lord...

1326
01:37:55,687 --> 01:37:58,392
...a bishop, an ambassador.
It's absolutely impossible.

1327
01:37:58,481 --> 01:38:02,017
Higgins, I'm trying to tell you
that I want to call off the bet.

1328
01:38:02,111 --> 01:38:04,352
I know you're a stubborn man, but so am l.

1329
01:38:04,446 --> 01:38:06,355
This experiment is over.

1330
01:38:06,448 --> 01:38:10,777
And nothing short of an order
from the king could force me to recant.

1331
01:38:12,787 --> 01:38:15,159
You understand, Higgins? It's over.

1332
01:38:16,916 --> 01:38:19,703
Higgins, if there's any mishap
at the Embassy tonight...

1333
01:38:19,794 --> 01:38:22,416
...if Miss Doolittle suffers
any embarrassment...

1334
01:38:22,505 --> 01:38:23,750
...it'll be on your head alone.

1335
01:38:23,840 --> 01:38:25,085
Eliza can do anything.

1336
01:38:25,174 --> 01:38:26,965
Suppose she's discovered?
Remember Ascot.

1337
01:38:27,051 --> 01:38:28,924
Suppose she makes
another ghastly mistake?

1338
01:38:29,011 --> 01:38:31,683
There'll be no horses at the ball, Pickering.

1339
01:38:33,726 --> 01:38:36,015
Think of how agonizing it would be.

1340
01:38:36,103 --> 01:38:38,772
If anything happened tonight,
I don't know what I'd do.

1341
01:38:38,856 --> 01:38:40,433
You could always rejoin your regiment.

1342
01:38:40,524 --> 01:38:42,351
This is no time for flippancy, Higgins.

1343
01:38:42,443 --> 01:38:44,482
The way you've driven her
the last six weeks...

1344
01:38:44,570 --> 01:38:46,646
...has exceeded all bounds
of common decency.

1345
01:38:46,738 --> 01:38:49,739
For God's sake, stop pacing.
Can't you settle somewhere?

1346
01:38:49,824 --> 01:38:51,782
Have some port. It'll quieten your nerves.

1347
01:38:51,869 --> 01:38:53,197
I'm not nervous.

1348
01:38:54,830 --> 01:38:56,739
-Where is it?
-On the piano.

1349
01:38:58,291 --> 01:38:59,619
The car's here, sir.

1350
01:38:59,709 --> 01:39:01,370
Good. Tell Miss Doolittle.

1351
01:39:01,462 --> 01:39:05,079
Tell Miss Doolittle indeed.
I'll bet you that damned gown doesn't fit.

1352
01:39:05,173 --> 01:39:07,249
I warned you about these French designers.

1353
01:39:07,342 --> 01:39:10,676
We should've gone to an English shop.
They would've been on our side.

1354
01:39:10,762 --> 01:39:13,087
-Have a glass of port?
-No, thank you.

1355
01:39:19,436 --> 01:39:23,650
Are you so sure this girl will retain
everything you've hammered into her?

1356
01:39:24,235 --> 01:39:25,895
Well, we shall see.

1357
01:39:26,237 --> 01:39:27,779
Suppose she doesn't?

1358
01:39:29,031 --> 01:39:30,574
I lose my bet.

1359
01:39:30,742 --> 01:39:34,406
There's one thing I can't stand about you,
your confounded complacency.

1360
01:39:34,495 --> 01:39:36,534
At a moment like this,
with so much at stake...

1361
01:39:36,622 --> 01:39:40,121
...it's utterly indecent
that you don't need a glass of port.

1362
01:39:41,794 --> 01:39:45,542
And what about the girl? You act
as though she doesn't matter at all.

1363
01:39:45,631 --> 01:39:48,252
Rubbish, Pickering. Of course she matters.

1364
01:39:48,633 --> 01:39:51,042
What do you think I've been doing
all these months?

1365
01:39:51,137 --> 01:39:54,635
What could possibly matter more
than to take a human being...

1366
01:39:54,723 --> 01:39:58,934
...and change her into a different human
being by creating a new speech for her?

1367
01:39:59,018 --> 01:40:02,767
It's filling up the deepest gap
that separates class from class...

1368
01:40:02,939 --> 01:40:04,517
...and soul from soul.

1369
01:40:04,941 --> 01:40:07,610
Oh, she matters immensely.

1370
01:40:29,718 --> 01:40:32,209
Miss Doolittle, you look beautiful.

1371
01:40:32,888 --> 01:40:34,465
Thank you, Colonel Pickering.

1372
01:40:34,556 --> 01:40:36,465
Don't you think so, Higgins?

1373
01:40:39,185 --> 01:40:41,855
Not bad. Not bad at all.

1374
01:43:42,536 --> 01:43:44,991
Maestro! Maestro!

1375
01:43:47,249 --> 01:43:48,411
Don't you remember me?

1376
01:43:48,500 --> 01:43:50,125
No. Who the devil are you?

1377
01:43:50,211 --> 01:43:53,661
I'm your pupil. Your first, your greatest,
your best pupil.

1378
01:43:53,797 --> 01:43:56,288
I'm Zoltan Karpathy, that marvelous boy.

1379
01:43:57,467 --> 01:43:59,424
I made your name famous
throughout Europe.

1380
01:43:59,510 --> 01:44:01,420
You teach me phonetics.
You can't forget me.

1381
01:44:01,513 --> 01:44:03,256
Why don't you have your hair cut?

1382
01:44:03,348 --> 01:44:06,882
I don't have your imposing appearance,
your figure, your brow.

1383
01:44:07,018 --> 01:44:09,057
If I had my hair cut,
nobody would notice me.

1384
01:44:09,145 --> 01:44:10,972
Where did you get these old coins?

1385
01:44:11,064 --> 01:44:13,056
These are decorations for languages.

1386
01:44:13,149 --> 01:44:14,892
The Queen of Transylvania is here.

1387
01:44:14,984 --> 01:44:18,103
I'm indispensable to her
at these official international parties.

1388
01:44:18,195 --> 01:44:21,115
I speak 32 languages.
I know everyone in Europe.

1389
01:44:21,201 --> 01:44:23,276
No imposter can escape my detection.

1390
01:44:23,369 --> 01:44:25,362
Professor Karpathy.

1391
01:44:27,539 --> 01:44:29,081
The Greek ambassador.

1392
01:44:29,875 --> 01:44:30,955
Greek, my foot!

1393
01:44:31,043 --> 01:44:33,830
He pretends not to know English,
but he can't deceive me.

1394
01:44:33,921 --> 01:44:36,328
He's the son of a Yorkshire watchmaker.

1395
01:44:37,049 --> 01:44:40,465
He speaks English so villainously
that he cannot utter a word...

1396
01:44:40,553 --> 01:44:42,794
...without betraying his origin.

1397
01:44:42,888 --> 01:44:46,636
I help him pretend, but make him pay
through the nose. I make them all pay.

1398
01:44:46,725 --> 01:44:50,011
Excuse me, sir, you are wanted upstairs.
Her Excellency asked for you.

1399
01:45:09,747 --> 01:45:11,742
Viscount and Viscountess Saxon.

1400
01:45:15,130 --> 01:45:18,001
Baron and Baroness of Yorkshire.

1401
01:45:19,718 --> 01:45:22,553
Sir Guy and Lady Scot-Auckland.

1402
01:45:42,407 --> 01:45:44,565
The Count and Countess Demereau.

1403
01:45:45,284 --> 01:45:47,775
The Viscount and Viscountess Hillyard.

1404
01:45:47,953 --> 01:45:50,825
Mr. and Mrs. Richard Lanser.

1405
01:45:51,457 --> 01:45:54,078
Lord and Lady Clanders.

1406
01:45:54,752 --> 01:45:57,622
Miss Eliza Doolittle, Colonel Pickering.

1407
01:45:57,963 --> 01:46:01,548
Miss Eliza Doolittle. Colonel Pickering.

1408
01:46:01,969 --> 01:46:03,962
Professor Higgins.

1409
01:46:04,472 --> 01:46:06,547
-Your Excellency.
-Miss Doolittle.

1410
01:46:06,640 --> 01:46:07,920
How do you do?

1411
01:46:08,016 --> 01:46:10,306
-Good evening, Colonel.
-Good evening.

1412
01:46:11,729 --> 01:46:15,062
What an enchanting young lady
you have with you this evening.

1413
01:46:15,149 --> 01:46:16,559
Well, who is she?

1414
01:46:16,942 --> 01:46:20,643
Oh, a cousin of mine. And Higgins.
Excuse me.

1415
01:46:20,988 --> 01:46:22,316
Professor Higgins.

1416
01:46:22,406 --> 01:46:26,485
Such a faraway look,
as if she's always lived in a garden.

1417
01:46:26,826 --> 01:46:28,984
So she has. A sort of garden.

1418
01:46:57,858 --> 01:47:01,310
Henry must take Eliza home at once.
There's a language expert here.

1419
01:47:01,404 --> 01:47:04,570
-Sort of, you know, '"imposterologist.'"
-I beg you pardon?

1420
01:47:05,324 --> 01:47:07,862
The young lady with Colonel Pickering....

1421
01:47:07,993 --> 01:47:09,570
Find out who she is.

1422
01:47:09,829 --> 01:47:11,074
With pleasure.

1423
01:47:11,539 --> 01:47:14,029
The whole situation is highly explosive.

1424
01:47:19,838 --> 01:47:22,412
Tell me, Zoltan,
some more about the Greek ambassador.

1425
01:47:22,507 --> 01:47:26,090
Gladly, but first I would love you
to present me to this glorious creature.

1426
01:47:26,177 --> 01:47:28,383
Does he really come from Yorkshire?

1427
01:47:37,230 --> 01:47:40,067
Her Majesty, the Queen of Transylvania...

1428
01:47:40,360 --> 01:47:43,526
...and His Royal Highness Prince Gregor.

1429
01:48:29,618 --> 01:48:32,109
Charming. Quite charming.

1430
01:48:33,455 --> 01:48:35,246
Miss Doolittle, Madam.

1431
01:50:11,346 --> 01:50:14,382
Miss Doolittle, my son would like
to dance with you.

1432
01:53:21,035 --> 01:53:22,862
Absolutely fantastic.

1433
01:53:26,331 --> 01:53:27,790
A lot of tomfoolery.

1434
01:53:27,874 --> 01:53:29,917
It was an immense achievement.

1435
01:53:30,004 --> 01:53:31,463
Well, Mr. Higgins?

1436
01:53:31,923 --> 01:53:35,042
A triumph, Mrs. Pearce. A total triumph.

1437
01:53:35,342 --> 01:53:38,793
Higgins, you were superb,
absolutely superb.

1438
01:53:39,013 --> 01:53:42,962
Tell us the truth now, weren't you
a little bit nervous once or twice?

1439
01:53:43,100 --> 01:53:44,843
Not during the whole evening?

1440
01:53:44,935 --> 01:53:46,595
Not when I saw we were going to win.

1441
01:53:46,686 --> 01:53:48,679
I felt like a bear in a cage hanging about.

1442
01:53:48,771 --> 01:53:50,432
It was an immense achievement.

1443
01:53:50,524 --> 01:53:53,608
If I hadn't backed myself to do it,
I'd have given up two months ago.

1444
01:53:53,693 --> 01:53:55,022
Absolutely fantastic.

1445
01:53:55,111 --> 01:53:56,653
Yes, a lot of tomfoolery.

1446
01:53:56,738 --> 01:53:58,695
Higgins, I salute you.

1447
01:53:58,781 --> 01:54:01,533
The silly people don't know
their own silly business.

1448
01:54:01,618 --> 01:54:04,618
'"Tonight, old man, you did it
You did it, you did it

1449
01:54:04,787 --> 01:54:07,657
'"You said that you would do it
And indeed you did

1450
01:54:07,748 --> 01:54:10,750
'"l thought that you would rue it
I doubted you'd do it

1451
01:54:10,835 --> 01:54:13,789
'"But now I must admit it
That succeed you did

1452
01:54:14,005 --> 01:54:16,626
'"You should get a medal
Or be even made a knight

1453
01:54:16,715 --> 01:54:19,387
'"Oh, it was nothing, really nothing

1454
01:54:20,096 --> 01:54:22,848
'"All alone you hurdled
Every obstacle in sight

1455
01:54:23,099 --> 01:54:26,265
'"Now wait, now wait
Give credit where it's due

1456
01:54:26,393 --> 01:54:28,884
'"A lot of the glory goes to you

1457
01:54:29,605 --> 01:54:32,641
'"But you're the one who did it
Who did it, who did it

1458
01:54:32,733 --> 01:54:35,650
'"As sturdy as Gibraltar
Not a second did you falter

1459
01:54:35,736 --> 01:54:37,016
'"There's no doubt about it

1460
01:54:37,112 --> 01:54:40,398
'"You did it!

1461
01:54:43,619 --> 01:54:47,746
'"l must have aged a year tonight
At times I thought I'd die of fright

1462
01:54:47,997 --> 01:54:50,703
'"Never was there a momentary lull

1463
01:54:51,877 --> 01:54:55,874
'"Shortly after we came in
I saw at once we'd easily win

1464
01:54:56,005 --> 01:54:58,757
'"And after that I found it deadly dull

1465
01:55:00,051 --> 01:55:02,259
'"You should have heard
The 'oohs' and 'aahs'

1466
01:55:02,346 --> 01:55:04,338
'"Everyone wondering who she was

1467
01:55:04,431 --> 01:55:07,100
'"You'd think they'd never seen
a lady before

1468
01:55:07,809 --> 01:55:12,141
'"And when the Prince of Transylvania
Asked to meet her

1469
01:55:13,108 --> 01:55:16,607
'"And gave his arm to lead her to the floor

1470
01:55:18,154 --> 01:55:21,441
'"l said to him: 'You did it
You did it, you did it'

1471
01:55:21,533 --> 01:55:24,700
'"They thought she was ecstatic
And so damned aristocratic

1472
01:55:24,786 --> 01:55:27,277
'"And they never knew
That you...

1473
01:55:29,291 --> 01:55:30,454
'"...did it'"

1474
01:55:32,669 --> 01:55:34,542
Thank goodness for Zoltan Karpathy.

1475
01:55:34,629 --> 01:55:36,871
If it hadn't been for him
I would've died of boredom.

1476
01:55:36,964 --> 01:55:39,207
Karpathy? That dreadful Hungarian?
Was he there?

1477
01:55:39,301 --> 01:55:42,385
Yes, he was there all right
and up to his old tricks.

1478
01:55:42,595 --> 01:55:45,050
'"That blackguard
Who uses the science of speech

1479
01:55:45,139 --> 01:55:47,677
'"More to blackmail and swindle than teach

1480
01:55:48,267 --> 01:55:50,758
'"He made it the devilish business of his

1481
01:55:51,062 --> 01:55:54,062
'"To find out who this Miss Doolittle is

1482
01:55:55,065 --> 01:55:57,521
'"Every time we looked around
There he was

1483
01:55:57,651 --> 01:55:59,812
'"That hairy hound from Budapest

1484
01:56:01,824 --> 01:56:04,825
'"Never leaving us alone
Never have I ever known

1485
01:56:04,910 --> 01:56:06,190
'"A ruder pest

1486
01:56:08,163 --> 01:56:12,410
'"Finally I decided it was foolish
Not to let him have his chance with her

1487
01:56:14,461 --> 01:56:18,458
'"So I stepped aside
And let him dance with her

1488
01:56:20,217 --> 01:56:25,341
'"Oozing charm from every pore
He oiled his way around the floor

1489
01:56:25,680 --> 01:56:30,010
'"Every trick that he could play
He used to strip her mask away

1490
01:56:30,477 --> 01:56:34,557
'"And when at last the dance was done
He glowed as if he knew he'd won

1491
01:56:35,356 --> 01:56:38,476
'"And with a voice too eager
And a smile too broad

1492
01:56:38,985 --> 01:56:42,484
'"He announced to the hostess
That she was a fraud'"

1493
01:56:43,406 --> 01:56:44,686
No!

1494
01:56:50,165 --> 01:56:54,577
'"'Her English is too good,' he said
'That clearly indicates that she is foreign

1495
01:56:56,670 --> 01:56:59,458
'"'Whereas others are instructed
ln their native language

1496
01:56:59,549 --> 01:57:01,340
'"'English people aren't

1497
01:57:03,010 --> 01:57:07,671
'"'Although she may have studied with
an expert dialectician and grammarian

1498
01:57:09,850 --> 01:57:14,512
'"'l can tell that she was born

1499
01:57:15,939 --> 01:57:17,314
'"'Hungarian'

1500
01:57:18,776 --> 01:57:21,231
'"Not only Hungarian but of royal blood

1501
01:57:22,362 --> 01:57:24,354
'"She is a princess

1502
01:57:24,697 --> 01:57:28,529
'"'Her blood,' he said
'ls bluer than the Danube is or ever was

1503
01:57:28,660 --> 01:57:31,614
'"'Royalty is absolutely written on her face

1504
01:57:31,705 --> 01:57:34,741
'"'She thought I was taken in
But actually I never was

1505
01:57:34,874 --> 01:57:37,874
'"'How could she deceive
Another member of her race?

1506
01:57:38,419 --> 01:57:42,798
'"'l know each language on the map'
Said he

1507
01:57:43,051 --> 01:57:47,344
'"'And she's Hungarian
As the first Hungarian Rhapsody''"

1508
01:57:55,354 --> 01:57:59,186
'"Congratulations, Professor Higgins

1509
01:57:59,567 --> 01:58:03,066
'"For your glorious victory

1510
01:58:03,320 --> 01:58:07,068
'"Congratulations, Professor Higgins

1511
01:58:07,490 --> 01:58:10,942
'"You'll be mentioned in history'"

1512
01:58:33,643 --> 01:58:35,849
Well, thank God, that's over.

1513
01:58:36,395 --> 01:58:39,101
Now I can go to bed
without dreading tomorrow.

1514
01:58:41,526 --> 01:58:43,851
-Good night, Mr. Higgins.
-Good night, Mrs. Pearce.

1515
01:58:43,945 --> 01:58:47,812
I think I'll turn in, too. Good night.
It's been a great occasion.

1516
01:58:47,906 --> 01:58:49,532
Good night, Pickering.

1517
01:58:50,451 --> 01:58:51,780
Mrs. Pearce?

1518
01:58:52,703 --> 01:58:56,914
Damn, I meant to ask her to give me coffee
in the morning instead of tea.

1519
01:58:57,541 --> 01:59:01,373
Leave a little note for her will you, Eliza.
And put out the lights.

1520
01:59:49,135 --> 01:59:51,708
Must be downstairs. Oh, darn it.

1521
01:59:52,096 --> 01:59:53,923
I'll leave my head behind
one of these days.

1522
01:59:54,014 --> 01:59:56,636
What the devil have I done
with my slippers?

1523
01:59:59,354 --> 02:00:01,062
Here are your slippers!

1524
02:00:06,360 --> 02:00:10,147
Take your slippers and may you never
have a day's luck with them.

1525
02:00:10,867 --> 02:00:12,860
What on earth? What's the matter?

1526
02:00:12,952 --> 02:00:14,612
Is anything wrong?

1527
02:00:14,746 --> 02:00:17,699
No, nothing's wrong with you.
I won your bet for you, haven't l?

1528
02:00:17,790 --> 02:00:20,661
That's enough for you!
I don't matter, I suppose?

1529
02:00:21,252 --> 02:00:24,870
You won my bet?
You presumptuous insect! I won it!

1530
02:00:24,964 --> 02:00:26,623
Why did you throw the slippers at me?

1531
02:00:26,715 --> 02:00:30,167
Because I wanted to smash your face.
I could kill you, you selfish brute!

1532
02:00:30,261 --> 02:00:32,419
Why didn't you leave me
where you picked me up?

1533
02:00:32,513 --> 02:00:36,296
You thank God it's all over. Now you can
throw me back again! Do you?

1534
02:00:36,391 --> 02:00:38,965
Oh, so the creature's nervous after all?

1535
02:00:42,231 --> 02:00:44,804
Claws in, you cat!
How dare you show your temper to me?

1536
02:00:44,900 --> 02:00:46,477
Sit down and be quiet!

1537
02:00:46,568 --> 02:00:49,190
What's to become of me?

1538
02:00:52,365 --> 02:00:54,274
How do I know what's to become of you?

1539
02:00:54,367 --> 02:00:55,565
What does it matter?

1540
02:00:55,660 --> 02:00:58,332
You don't care. I know you don't care.

1541
02:00:58,415 --> 02:01:00,906
You wouldn't care if I was dead.
I'm nothing to you.

1542
02:01:01,001 --> 02:01:02,874
Not as much as them slippers.

1543
02:01:02,961 --> 02:01:04,040
Those slippers!

1544
02:01:04,129 --> 02:01:07,793
Those slippers! I didn't think it meant
any difference now.

1545
02:01:11,386 --> 02:01:14,137
Why have you suddenly begun
going on like this?

1546
02:01:14,472 --> 02:01:17,141
May I ask if you complain
of your treatment here?

1547
02:01:17,224 --> 02:01:18,054
No.

1548
02:01:18,183 --> 02:01:21,304
Has anybody behaved badly?
Colonel Pickering, Mrs. Pearce?

1549
02:01:21,396 --> 02:01:22,427
No.

1550
02:01:22,730 --> 02:01:25,814
Well you don't pretend
that I have treated you badly?

1551
02:01:26,608 --> 02:01:27,639
No.

1552
02:01:27,734 --> 02:01:29,644
Well, I'm glad to hear that.

1553
02:01:30,655 --> 02:01:33,525
Perhaps you're tired
after the strain of the day.

1554
02:01:34,199 --> 02:01:36,571
Would you have a chocolate?

1555
02:01:36,910 --> 02:01:39,402
No, thank you.

1556
02:01:41,582 --> 02:01:45,579
Well, it's only natural that you should
be anxious, but it's all over now.

1557
02:01:45,668 --> 02:01:47,542
Nothing more to worry about.

1558
02:01:47,629 --> 02:01:50,502
No, nothing more for you to worry about.

1559
02:01:51,843 --> 02:01:54,548
Oh, God, I wish I was dead.

1560
02:01:55,180 --> 02:01:57,753
Why? ln heaven's name, why?

1561
02:01:58,600 --> 02:02:02,348
Now listen to me, Eliza.
All this irritation is purely subjective.

1562
02:02:02,729 --> 02:02:04,970
I don't understand. I'm too ignorant.

1563
02:02:05,064 --> 02:02:08,564
It's just imagination. Nothing's wrong.
Nobody's hurting you.

1564
02:02:08,652 --> 02:02:09,850
Go to bed and sleep it off.

1565
02:02:09,944 --> 02:02:14,405
Have a little cry and say your prayers.
You'll feel very much more comfortable.

1566
02:02:14,740 --> 02:02:16,567
I heard your prayers.

1567
02:02:16,742 --> 02:02:18,486
'"Thank God it's all over.'"

1568
02:02:18,620 --> 02:02:20,327
Don't you thank God it's all over?

1569
02:02:20,413 --> 02:02:22,820
Now you're free,
and you can do what you like.

1570
02:02:22,915 --> 02:02:26,034
Oh, what am I fit for?
What have you left me fit for?

1571
02:02:26,752 --> 02:02:29,504
Where am I to go? What am I to do?

1572
02:02:30,131 --> 02:02:32,206
And what's to become of me?

1573
02:02:33,300 --> 02:02:36,135
That's what's worrying you, is it?

1574
02:02:37,762 --> 02:02:39,722
I wouldn't worry about that if I were you.

1575
02:02:39,809 --> 02:02:44,221
I'm sure you won't have any difficulty
in settling yourself somewhere or other.

1576
02:02:46,982 --> 02:02:49,604
I didn't quite realize you were going away.

1577
02:02:50,652 --> 02:02:52,609
You might marry, you know.

1578
02:02:52,988 --> 02:02:56,901
You see, Eliza, all men are not confirmed
old bachelors like me and the Colonel.

1579
02:02:56,991 --> 02:02:59,993
Most men are the marrying sort,
poor devils.

1580
02:03:00,745 --> 02:03:01,741
You're not bad-looking.

1581
02:03:01,830 --> 02:03:04,320
You're really quite a pleasure
to look at sometimes.

1582
02:03:04,415 --> 02:03:05,957
Not now, when you've been crying.

1583
02:03:06,042 --> 02:03:07,833
You look like the very devil, but...

1584
02:03:07,918 --> 02:03:12,379
...when you're all right and quite yourself
you're what I would call attractive.

1585
02:03:14,300 --> 02:03:16,625
Go to bed, have a good rest,
get up in the morning...

1586
02:03:16,719 --> 02:03:20,503
...and have a look at yourself in the glass.
You won't feel so bad.

1587
02:03:24,977 --> 02:03:28,811
I daresay, my mother might find some
fellow or other who would do very well.

1588
02:03:28,900 --> 02:03:31,022
We were above that at Covent Garden.

1589
02:03:31,110 --> 02:03:32,569
What do you mean?

1590
02:03:32,778 --> 02:03:35,316
I sold flowers, I didn't sell myself.

1591
02:03:36,073 --> 02:03:39,193
Now you've made a lady of me,
I'm not fit to sell anything else.

1592
02:03:39,285 --> 02:03:41,954
Oh, tosh, Eliza.
Don't insult human relations...

1593
02:03:42,037 --> 02:03:45,073
...by dragging all that cant
about buying and selling into it.

1594
02:03:45,165 --> 02:03:47,241
Don't marry the fellow if you don't want to.

1595
02:03:47,333 --> 02:03:48,959
What else am I to do?

1596
02:03:49,044 --> 02:03:50,871
Oh, there are lots of things.

1597
02:03:50,962 --> 02:03:53,370
What about the old idea of a florist shop?

1598
02:03:53,465 --> 02:03:56,501
I'm sure Pickering'd set you up in one.
He's got lots of money.

1599
02:03:56,592 --> 02:03:58,550
He'll pay for all those togs you're wearing.

1600
02:03:58,637 --> 02:04:02,716
And that with the hire of the jewelry'll
make a big hole in 200 pounds.

1601
02:04:02,932 --> 02:04:05,304
Come on now. You'll be all right.

1602
02:04:06,477 --> 02:04:09,644
Well, I must be off to bed.
I'm really devilish sleepy.

1603
02:04:10,982 --> 02:04:13,270
I was looking for something. What was it?

1604
02:04:13,359 --> 02:04:14,557
Your slippers.

1605
02:04:15,069 --> 02:04:17,820
Oh, yes, of course. You shied them at me.

1606
02:04:18,950 --> 02:04:21,238
Before you go, sir.

1607
02:04:24,997 --> 02:04:27,998
Do my clothes belong to me
or to Colonel Pickering?

1608
02:04:29,085 --> 02:04:31,291
What the devil use would they be
to Pickering?

1609
02:04:31,378 --> 02:04:33,371
Why bother about that
in the middle of the night?

1610
02:04:33,464 --> 02:04:34,922
What may I take away with me?

1611
02:04:35,007 --> 02:04:37,414
I don't want to be accused of stealing.

1612
02:04:38,094 --> 02:04:39,173
Stealing?

1613
02:04:40,262 --> 02:04:43,547
You shouldn't have said that.
That shows a want of feeling.

1614
02:04:43,640 --> 02:04:47,684
I'm sorry. I'm a common, ignorant girl
and in my station I have to be careful.

1615
02:04:47,769 --> 02:04:51,222
There can't be any feelings between
the likes of you and the likes of me.

1616
02:04:51,315 --> 02:04:54,814
Please, will you tell me
what belongs to me and what doesn't?

1617
02:04:55,277 --> 02:04:57,649
Take the whole damned houseful
if you want.

1618
02:04:57,738 --> 02:05:00,490
Except the jewelry. That's hired.
Will that satisfy you?

1619
02:05:00,574 --> 02:05:01,819
Stop, please.

1620
02:05:04,036 --> 02:05:07,072
Will you take these to your room
and keep them safe?

1621
02:05:07,917 --> 02:05:10,834
I don't want to run the risk
of them being missed.

1622
02:05:12,421 --> 02:05:15,920
Hand them over! lf these belonged
to me and not the jeweler, I'd...

1623
02:05:16,007 --> 02:05:18,581
...l'd ram them down
your ungrateful throat.

1624
02:05:18,886 --> 02:05:22,965
The ring isn't the jeweler's.
It's the one you bought me in Brighton.

1625
02:05:24,307 --> 02:05:25,849
I don't want it now.

1626
02:05:29,104 --> 02:05:30,764
Don't you hit me!

1627
02:05:31,273 --> 02:05:34,439
Hit you? You infamous creature!
How dare you suggest such a thing!

1628
02:05:34,525 --> 02:05:37,194
It's you who've hit me.
You've wounded me to the heart.

1629
02:05:37,278 --> 02:05:40,861
I'm glad. I've got a little
of my own back anyhow.

1630
02:05:42,033 --> 02:05:45,615
You've caused me to lose my temper.
That's hardly happened to me before.

1631
02:05:45,703 --> 02:05:48,491
I don't wish to discuss it further tonight.
I'm going to bed.

1632
02:05:48,581 --> 02:05:51,154
Leave your own note for Mrs. Pearce
about the coffee...

1633
02:05:51,250 --> 02:05:52,828
...for it won't be done by me!

1634
02:05:52,918 --> 02:05:56,501
Damn Mrs. Pearce,
damn the coffee and damn you!

1635
02:05:57,759 --> 02:06:01,008
Damn my own folly for having lavished
my hard-earned knowledge...

1636
02:06:01,095 --> 02:06:05,258
...and the treasure of my regard
and intimacy on a heartless guttersnipe!

1637
02:06:56,525 --> 02:07:01,152
'"Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait!

1638
02:07:03,115 --> 02:07:07,361
'"You'll be sorry
But your tears will be too late

1639
02:07:09,371 --> 02:07:12,242
'"You will be the one it's done to

1640
02:07:13,041 --> 02:07:16,291
'"And you'll have no one to run to

1641
02:07:16,878 --> 02:07:18,456
'"Just you wait'"

1642
02:07:47,159 --> 02:07:51,905
'"l have often walked
down this street before

1643
02:07:52,915 --> 02:07:57,743
'"But the pavement always stayed
beneath my feet before

1644
02:07:58,671 --> 02:08:03,712
'"All at once am I several stories high

1645
02:08:04,509 --> 02:08:09,053
'"Knowing I'm on the street where you live

1646
02:08:10,516 --> 02:08:15,260
'"Are there lilac trees in the heart of town?

1647
02:08:16,354 --> 02:08:21,265
'"Can you hear a lark
in any other part of town?

1648
02:08:22,360 --> 02:08:27,523
'"Does enchantment pour
out of every door?

1649
02:08:28,285 --> 02:08:32,827
'"No, it's just on the street where you live

1650
02:08:34,332 --> 02:08:38,959
'"And, oh, the towering feeling

1651
02:08:39,879 --> 02:08:44,624
'"Just to know somehow you are near

1652
02:08:46,218 --> 02:08:50,631
'"The overpowering feeling

1653
02:08:51,307 --> 02:08:56,217
'"That any second you may suddenly appear

1654
02:08:57,688 --> 02:09:00,938
'"People stop and stare, they don't....'"

1655
02:09:07,698 --> 02:09:08,729
Darling.

1656
02:09:10,158 --> 02:09:11,902
Freddy, whatever are you doing here?

1657
02:09:11,993 --> 02:09:15,860
Nothing. I spend most of my nights here.
It's the only place where I'm happy.

1658
